## Introduction  
Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) regression is the statistical equivalent of that one friend who shows up to every party, claims to have your best interests at heart, and then proceeds to lecture you about how *everything* can be explained by a straight line. [Regression analysis](/Regression_analysis) isn’t just a fancy term for “drawing a line through data points”; it’s the methodological backbone of countless [social science](/Social_science) papers, economics textbooks, and the occasional [political poll](/Political_polling) that pretends to be scientific. In short, OLS is the method that pretends to be simple enough for a teenager to grasp, yet complex enough to make a seasoned statistician sigh into their coffee.  

### What it actually does  
At its core, OLS seeks to minimize the **Residual sum of squares** ([RSS](/Residual_sum_of_squares))—the cumulative squared differences between observed values and the values predicted by a linear model. If you’ve ever stared at a scatter plot and thought, “Surely a straight line could make this look less chaotic,” OLS is the algorithmic answer to that naive optimism.  

### Why it matters (and why you’ll pretend to understand it)  
Because OLS is the go‑to tool for estimating **Coefficient of determination** ([R²](/Coefficient_of_determination)) and other assorted metrics that make researchers feel like they’re uncovering deep truths about the universe. It also serves as the baseline against which more sophisticated techniques—like [Robust regression](/Robust_regression) or [Bayesian inference](/Bayesian_inference)—are judged. In other words, if you can’t beat OLS, you probably need a better excuse for not publishing.  

